Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audit
We have performed audits of the financial statements of The Prudential Merged Retirement
Plan (the Plan), an employee benefit plan subject to the Employee Retirement Income Security
Act of 1974 (ERISA), as permitted by ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) (ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C)
audit). The financial statements comprise the statements of net assets available for benefits
(modified cash basis) as of December 31, 2024 and 2023, the related statements of changes in
net assets available for benefits (modified cash basis) for the years then ended, the statement
of accumulated plan benefits (modified cash basis) as of December 31, 2023, the related
statement of changes in accumulated plan benefits (modified cash basis) for the year then
ended, and the related notes to the financial statements.
Management, having determined it is permissible in the circumstances, has elected to have the
audits of the Plan’s financial statements performed in accordance with ERISA Section
103(a)(3)(C) pursuant to 29 CFR 2520.103-8 of the Department of Labor’s Rules and
Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA. As permitted by ERISA Section
103(a)(3)(C), our audits need not extend to any statements or information related to assets held
for investment of the Plan (investment information) by a bank or similar institution or insurance
carrier that is regulated, supervised, and subject to periodic examination by a state or federal
agency, provided that the statements or information regarding assets so held are prepared and
certified to by the bank or similar institution or insurance carrier in accordance with 29 CFR
2520.103-5 of the Department of Labor’s Rules and Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure
under ERISA (qualified institution).
Management has obtained certifications from qualified institutions as of December 31, 2024 and
2023, and for the years then ended, stating that the certified investment information, as
described in Note 4 to the financial statements, is complete and accurate.

Responsibilities of Management for the Financial Statements
Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements
in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America,
and for the design, implementation, and maintenance of internal control relevant to the
preparation and fair presentation of financial statements that are free from material
misstatement, whether due to fraud or error. Management’s election of the ERISA Section

Auditor’s Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements
Except as described in the Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audit section

1. Description of the Plan
The following description of The Prudential Merged Retirement Plan (the “Plan”) provides only general
information. Participants should refer to the Summary Plan Descriptions and Plan documents for a
complete description of the Plan's provisions.
General
The Plan is a non-contributory defined benefit pension plan that covers, in general, United States
employees and full-time statutory agents of The Prudential Insurance Company of America (the
“Company”) and its participating affiliates, other than employees excluded pursuant to collective
bargaining agreements.
The Plan has three components:
The Prudential Traditional Retirement Plan Document component (“Traditional Plan”) covering United
States employees and full-time statutory agents of the Company and its participating affiliates hired before
January 1, 2001 other than employees of Prudential Securities Incorporated (“PSI”).
The Prudential Securities Incorporated Cash Balance Pension Plan component (“PSI Plan”) is a frozen plan
covering former employees of PSI.
The Prudential Cash Balance Pension Plan Document component (“Cash Balance Plan”) covering United
States employees and full-time statutory agents of the Company and its participating affiliates hired on or
after January 1, 2001. Generally, participants in active service throughout 2001 were allowed to make an
irrevocable election to be covered by the Cash Balance Plan instead of the Traditional Plan.
The Plan is subject to the provisions of the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, as amended
(“ERISA”).
Pension Benefits
Generally, participants are eligible to receive pension benefits after the participant ends employment with
the Company and its affiliates, subject to the provisions of the respective component of the Plan.
Traditional Plan - Participants covered under the Traditional Plan generally are eligible to begin
receiving vested monthly benefits in various annuity forms beginning no later than the
participants’ normal retirement date (age 65), based on a benefit formula that considers age, years
of service and eligible earnings (for a limited period preceding separation from service) as defined
in the Plan. Reduced monthly pension benefits may begin as early as age 55.
PSI Plan - Participants covered under the PSI Plan are generally entitled to pension benefits at any
time following the date the participant ends employment with the Company and its affiliates based
on a benefit formula that considers age, years of service and earnings for each month of
employment with PSI. Benefit accruals were frozen under the PSI component effective as of
December 31, 2003; as a result, Service and Transition Credits, as applicable, ceased and no
individual became a participant in the PSI component after December 31, 2003. Participant’s
accounts are credited on a monthly basis with a Plan rate of interest until benefits are distributed.
Under the PSI Plan, normal retirement means the date a participant reaches age 65. Participants
may elect to receive their benefits in several forms, including lump sum benefit payments.

Cash Balance Plan - Vested participants covered under the Cash Balance Plan are generally
eligible to begin receiving pension benefits as of the first day of the month following the date the
participant ends employment with the Company and its affiliates, but no later than the normal
retirement date (age 65). The benefit formula considers age, years of service, and eligible monthly
earnings as defined in the Plan. The benefit is tracked as additions or credits to a notional cash
balance account established for each participant. The account is also credited on a monthly basis
with a Plan rate of interest until withdrawn. Participants may elect to receive their benefits in
several forms, including as a lump sum distribution. Participants electing a lump sum payment
generally may elect to have the payment rolled over to another tax-qualified plan, including The
Prudential Employee Savings Plan.
Death Benefits
Unless otherwise elected by the participant, death benefits generally are paid to a surviving spouse or to a
beneficiary based on a form of payment elected by the participant.
Vesting
Generally, participants are considered 100% vested after completing three years of vesting service.
2. Summary of Significant Accounting Policies
Basis of Accounting
The accompanying statements are prepared on a modified cash basis of accounting, which is a
comprehensive basis of accounting other than generally accepted accounting principles in the United States
of America ("U.S. GAAP"). The modified cash basis of accounting is a cash receipt and disbursement
method of accounting unlike U.S. GAAP where information is reported on an accrual basis. However,
under the modified cash basis of accounting investments are stated at their respective fair value, which is
consistent with U.S. GAAP.
Reclassifications
Certain prior year amounts were reclassified to conform to the current year's presentation.
Use of Estimates
The preparation of financial statements in accordance with a modified cash basis of accounting requires
management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities
and changes therein; disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities; and the actuarial present value of
accumulated plan benefits at the date of the financial statements, and changes therein. Actual results could
differ from those estimates.
Investment Valuation and Income Recognition
Investments are reported at fair value. Fair value is the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid
to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. See
Note 5 for a discussion of fair value measurements.
Purchases and sales of investments are recorded on a trade-date basis. Interest and other investment loss is
recorded when received. Net appreciation includes the Plan's gains and losses on investments bought and
sold as well as held during the year.
For futures contracts, changes in the value of the contract are recognized as unrealized gains or losses by
"marking to market" on a daily basis to reflect changes in the market value of the contract. When the
contract is closed, the Plan records a realized gain or loss equal to the difference between the value of the
contract on the closing date and the value of the contract when originated.

Payment of Benefits
Benefits are recorded when paid.
Administrative Expenses
In general, expenses are the obligations of the Plan and are paid or reimbursed from the Plan's assets
subject to compliance with applicable law. The Company, without obligation to do so in the future, may
pay selected expenses of the Plan; however, the Company must pay those expenses that cannot be paid or
reimbursed by the Plan under applicable legal rules. Expenses paid directly by the Company are excluded
from these financial statements. Certain investment related expenses are included in net appreciation in fair
value of investments presented in the accompanying Statements of Changes in Net Assets Available for
Benefits.
Actuarial Present Value of Accumulated Plan Benefits
Accumulated plan benefits are those future pension payments, including lump sum and periodic
distributions, attributable to the periods of service employees have rendered to the Company, as defined by
the Plan. Accumulated plan benefits include benefits expected to be paid to (a) retired or terminated
employees or their beneficiaries, (b) beneficiaries of employees who have died, and (c) present employees
or their beneficiaries.
The Company made an irrevocable commitment to pay the benefits for certain retirees and vested
terminated employees (see Note 7 for additional information on Part II of the GA-210 contract). Because
the benefits for these certain retirees and vested terminated employees are fully guaranteed by the
Company, they are considered annuitants rather than current plan participants ("Annuitants") and are
therefore excluded from the number of participants reported in Part II (Basic Plan Information) of Form
5500.
However, since the assets supporting the GA-210 contract remain in the Plan and benefit payments are
made from those assets, the actuarial assumptions for purposes of calculating the maximum funding
limitation for Schedule SB of Form 5500 and accumulated plan benefits presented in the Statement of
Accumulated Plan Benefits includes these Annuitants.
The actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits is determined by independent actuaries based on
information provided by the Company and is the amount that results from applying actuarial assumptions to
adjust the accumulated plan benefits to reflect the time value of money (through discounts for interest) and
the probability of payment (by means of decrements such as for death, disability, withdrawal or retirement)
between the valuation date (the date as of which the benefit information is presented) and the expected date
of payment.

3. Funding Policy
Contributions consist solely of amounts funded by the Company. It is the policy of the Company to fund
amounts which satisfy the minimum funding requirements of ERISA. The projected accrued benefit (unit
cost) method is used to determine normal cost. These factors are applied to pensionable earnings for the
year to produce the employer’s annual contribution. No contributions were required by the Company to the
Plan for the years ended December 31, 2024 and 2023, since the Plan is fully funded.
Although it has not expressed any intention to do so, the Company has the right under the Plan to freeze
future benefit accruals and to terminate the Plan, in whole or in part, subject to the provisions set forth in
ERISA. In the event the Plan terminates, the net assets of the Plan will be allocated among the participants
and beneficiaries of the Plan in the order provided for under Section 4044 of ERISA, and to the extent
unfunded vested benefits for active participants exist, ERISA provides that such benefits are payable by the
Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation (“PBGC”), up to the applicable limitation. Generally, the PBGC
guarantees vested normal age retirement benefits, early retirement benefits, and certain survivors’ pensions.
The amount of benefit protection is subject to certain limitations, and there is a ceiling on the amount of
monthly benefit the PBGC guarantees, which is adjusted periodically.

5. Fair Value Measurements
The framework for measuring fair value provides a fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to
valuation techniques used to measure fair value. The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted
quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (“Level 1” measurements) and the lowest
priority to unobservable inputs (“Level 3” measurements). The three levels of the fair value hierarchy are
described as follows:
Level 1 Inputs to the valuation methodology are unadjusted quoted prices for identical assets or
liabilities in active markets that the Plan has the ability to access.
Level 2 Inputs to the valuation methodology include:
• Quoted prices for similar assets or liabilities in active markets;
• Quoted prices for identical or similar assets or liabilities in inactive markets;
• Inputs other than quoted prices that are observable for the asset or liability;
• Inputs that are derived principally from or corroborated by observable market data by
correlation or other means.
If the asset or liability has a specified (contractual) term, the Level 2 input must be
observable for substantially the full term of the asset or liability.
Level 3 Inputs to the valuation methodology are unobservable and significant to the fair value
measurement.
The asset’s or liability’s fair value measurement level within the fair value hierarchy is based on the lowest
level of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement. Valuation techniques maximize the use
of relevant observable inputs and minimize the use of unobservable inputs.
The following is a description of the valuation methodologies used for assets measured at fair value. There
have been no changes in the methodologies used at December 31, 2024 and 2023.
Corporate Debt (Corporate Bonds, Asset–Backed Securities, Collateralized Mortgage Obligations,
Collateralized Loan Obligations) - Securities are priced using inputs such as benchmark yields, reported
trades, broker/dealer quotes, and issuer spreads; or priced using non-binding broker/dealer quotes.
U.S. Government Securities (Federal, Federal Agency, Mortgaged-Backed, State & Other) - Securities are
priced using inputs such as benchmark yields, reported trades, broker/dealer quotes, and issuer spreads; or
priced using non-binding broker/dealer quotes.
Insurance Company Separate Accounts and Common/Collective Trusts - The Plan values these investments
at unit value, which is based on the aggregate fair value of the underlying assets (primarily equity securities
and bonds) in relation to the total number of units outstanding. The unit value represents the price at which
the plan-directed transactions are effected. Unit value is the equivalent of NAV, which is a practical
expedient for estimating the fair value of these investments.
Hedge Funds - The value of interests in hedge funds is based on the underlying investments that include
equities, debt and other investments.

Partnerships - The value of interests owned by the Plan in partnerships are based on valuation by the
general partners of such partnerships determined in good faith using criteria set forth in the partnership

Registered Investment Companies - are mutual funds registered with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. The investments held by the Plan are deemed to be actively traded and the mutual funds are
required to publish their daily net asset values ("NAV") and to transact at that price. The Plan values these
investments at the closing price reported by the registered investment company on the reporting date.
Short Term Investments - Securities are valued initially at cost and thereafter are adjusted for amortization

different price would be more reflective of fair value.
Swaps - Value based on actively quoted or observable market values from external market data, third-party
pricing vendors, and/or recent trading activity.

6. Contract with Insurance Company
The Plan has an insurance contract, GA-210, with the Company. The contract provides a) in Part I for the
purchase from the Company of annuities for the payment by the Company of fixed dollar or variable
annuity benefits for certain retirees and vested terminated employees, and b) in Part II for the irrevocable
commitment by the Company to pay benefits, to the extent not paid by the Plan, for certain retirees and
vested terminated employees (“guaranteed benefits”).
The fixed dollar portion of Part I of GA-210, an allocated contract, supports fixed dollar annuities which
became payable before December 29, 1979 for specific retirees and terminated vested employees who are
no longer Plan participants. Accordingly, the assets of Part I are not included in the net assets available for
benefits, and the value of future benefit payments for these prior participants are not included in the
Statement of Accumulated Plan Benefits.
In 2000, the Variable Annuity portion of Part I of GA-210, which supports annuities for retirees with
benefits in the variable form, was amended to add the Prudential Variable Income Annuity Account (“VIA
Account”). Current and future variable annuitants may choose to have their monthly benefits paid in
amounts that vary, based on investment returns (in excess of an assumed rate) of any of the multiple
investment options underlying the sub-accounts in the VIA Account. All previously assured variable
benefits being paid under the contract were converted to VIA variable annuities on a non-participating
basis.
Part II of GA-210 establishes a Contract Liability Amount for fully guaranteed benefits due to other retirees
and vested terminated employees (Annuitants). The Contract Liability Amount is the value of the benefits,
which the Company is irrevocably committed to pay under Part II of this contract in the event such benefits
are not paid by the Plan. The benefits fully guaranteed under Part II are funded by separate accounts.
Subject to certain investment guidelines, the Plan retains control of the investments, manages the
investments by selecting separate accounts, and retains the risks and rewards of investment experience.
The Plan is required to maintain certain investments, with a value equal to or greater than the Contract
Liability Amount in the Company’s separate accounts. If however, through market losses or permitted

8. Related Party Transactions
The Company (or an affiliate) acts as the investment manager for a number of investments under the Plan.
To the extent a party-in-interest is involved, the transactions in these investments qualify as exempt party-
in-interest transactions under ERISA.
To the extent permitted by ERISA, the Plan pays the Company management fees for investment advisory
services. Generally, administrative expenses were paid by the Company. Certain administrative expenses,
to the extent permitted by ERISA, were reimbursed to the Company from the Plan. The Company also
assumed certain other investment advisory and administrative expenses related to the Plan for which it did
not seek reimbursement.
The Plan pays the Company annuity risk charges relating to the insurance contract (GA-210) between the
Company and the Plan that guarantees certain benefit payments of the Plan.
9. Tax Status
The IRS has determined and informed the Company by a letter, dated May 27, 2021, that the Plan, as
amended and restated effective January 1, 2020, and its related trust are designed in accordance with the
applicable sections of the IRC. The Plan administrator and the Plan’s tax counsel believe that the Plan
continues to be designed and is currently being operated in material conformity with the applicable
requirements of the IRC including the mandatory requirements of recent legislation (e.g., SECURE Act,
etc.).
U.S. GAAP requires Plan management to evaluate tax positions taken by the Plan and recognize a tax
liability (or asset) if it has taken an uncertain position that more likely than not would not be sustained upon
examination by the IRS. The Plan is subject to routine audits by taxing jurisdictions; however, there are
currently no audits for any tax periods in progress.
10. Derivative Financial Instruments
The Plan uses derivative financial instruments to manage risks associated with the Plan’s investment
portfolio, to lower transaction costs, or to enhance returns on investments in the Plan. The Plan primarily
uses futures contracts and interest-rate swaps and does not enter into highly leveraged or complex
derivative instruments.

11. Risks and Uncertainties
The Plan invests in various investment securities. Investment securities are exposed to various risks such
as interest rate, market and credit risks. Due to the level of risks associated with certain investment
securities, it is at least reasonably possible that changes in the values of investment securities will occur in
the near term and that such changes could materially affect the amounts reported in the Statements of Net
Assets Available for Benefits.
Plan contributions are made, and the actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits are reported based
on certain assumptions pertaining to interest rates, inflation rates and employee demographics, all of which
are subject to change. Due to uncertainties inherent in the estimations and assumptions process, it is at least
reasonably possible that changes in these estimates and assumptions in the near term would be material to
the financial statements.

Schedule SB, line 24—Change in Actuarial Assumptions
The funding valuation results reflect the following assumption changes:
 The graded table of rates used for the interest crediting assumption was updated.
 The withdrawal rates were updated to better reflect plan experience.
 The retirement rates were updated to better reflect plan experience.
 The involuntary termination assumption was updated to better reflect plan experience.
 The optional payment form assumptions for active participants were updated to better reflect plan
experience.
 The optional payment form assumptions for terminated vested participants were updated to better
reflect plan experience.
 The salary increase assumption was updated to better reflect plan experience.
 The retirement age assumption for terminated vested participants was updated to better reflect plan
experience.
These changes were made to better reflect anticipated plan experience. The assumption change did not
reduce the funding shortfall more than the thresholds stated in the Internal Revenue Section 430(h)(5); as
such, approval of the Commissioner is not required.

Plan Provisions—Merged Retirement Plan (Traditional Formula)
Eligibility for Participation All employees hired prior to January 1, 2001 who did not make a
valid election to be covered by the Cash Balance Formula. Also,
employees who had a benefit purchased in accordance with
these provisions prior to January 1, 2002 will continue to have
that portion of the benefit covered by these provisions.
Individuals hired on or after January 1, 2001 as well as former
employees of Prudential Securities Incorporated (PSI) are
covered by the Cash Balance formula.
Participation commences on the first day of United States
service for all employees except:
(a) those specifically excluded by a collective-bargaining
agreement;
(b) United States citizen in foreign service specifically excluded
by the company;
(c) nonresident aliens, unless specifically included;
(d) employees in nonparticipating affiliates;
(e) deemed non-employees;
(f) individuals not treated as employees;
Normal Retirement
Eligibility First of month coinciding with or next following the attainment of
age 65.
Pension Benefit
Basic Formula The sum of the following:
(1) 1.35% of participant’s earnings base plus 0.65% of
participant’s earnings base in excess of covered
compensation, multiplied by years of credited service not in
excess of 25 years.
(2) 0.75% of participant’s earnings base (1% for bargained
employees and special agents) plus 0.25% (0.35% for
bargained employees and special agents) of participant’s
earnings base in excess of covered compensation, multiplied
by years of credited service between 25 and 38 years.
(3) 1.00% of participant’s earnings base multiplied by years of
credited service in excess of 38 years.
(4) For agents who are at least 50 years old as of January 1,
1998, an additional benefit equal to 0.5% of participant’s
earnings base multiplied by credited service earned from age
50 to age 55 plus 1.0% of participant’s earnings base
multiplied by credited service earned after age 55.

Plan Provisions—Merged Retirement Plan (Cash Balance Formula)
Transition Credits
o
An eligible participant will receive Transition Credits
from January 1, 2002 through December 31, 2006. To
be eligible, the participant must have made a valid
election of the cash balance formula during the 2001
Pension Choice election period. These credits are in
addition to Basic Credits and equal 2.5% of the
participant’s compensation. Transition Credits will be
added to the participant’s account until the earlier of:
December 31, 2006; or
o
The end of the month following the date his
o
employment with Prudential Financial ends.
Interest credit
o
Each participant shall have interest credited to his
account at the end of each month based on the value
of his Cash Balance Account at the beginning of the
month. Interest credits are added to accounts each
month until the cash balance formula benefits are
distributed, even if the participant is no longer working
for Prudential Financial and its Affiliates. The interest
credit percentage is based on the monthly equivalent
of the average yield of 30-year U.S. Treasury
Securities for October (constant maturities) of the prior
year. In no event will the interest rate used be less
than the monthly equivalent of 4.25% per annum.
Other Information to Fully and Fairly Disclose the Actuarial Position of the Plan
Due to software limitations with the electronic filing process, information filed electronically cannot be controlled
by the Enrolled Actuary. The values on the signed Schedule SB will govern to the extent there are any differences
in the entries filed electronically and the actual data contained on the signed Schedule SB.
